# Layout Structure

<!-- Use `src/app/layout.tsx` (import as `@/app/layout.tsx`) as the reference for the **root** layout.  -->
Nested segment layouts follow the same structural ideas: minimal shell, clear provider boundaries, `{children}` where the route tree renders.

## 1) Role of a layout file

- A `layout.tsx` file defines **shared UI and wrappers** for a segment and all nested routes.
- It **must** export a default component that accepts `{ children }` (and optional parallel route slots if the app uses them).
- Layouts are **Server Components** by default; keep them async when you need server-only setup at this boundary (the root layout is `async` in this project).

**Do not** put large page-specific feature markup in a layout—keep that in `page.tsx` and `_components`.

## 2) Root layout: import order (reference)

Group imports in a stable order:

1. Next types (`Metadata`, `Viewport`) and React primitives (`Suspense`) as needed.
2. App-wide assets: `@/app/lib/fonts`, global CSS (`./globals.css`).
3. Cross-cutting providers and shell: `@/app/(_home)/_context/Modal`, `@/app/(_home)/_components/NavBar/NavBarShell`.

## 3) Metadata and viewport

- Export **`metadata`** (`title`, `description`, and other `Metadata` fields) from the root layout so the whole app inherits defaults.
- Export **`viewport`** when you need device scaling policy (this project sets width, scale, and `userScalable`).

Segment-specific layouts can export their own `metadata` / `generateMetadata` to override or extend for that subtree.

## 4) Document structure

- Render **exactly one** `<html>` and **one** `<body>` in the root layout.
- Set **`lang`** on `<html>` appropriately (`lang="en"` in the reference).
- Apply **body-level** concerns on `<body>`:
  - All `next/font` **`.variable`** classes so CSS variables exist app-wide.
  - Global Tailwind utilities from the design system (`antialiased`, `min-h-screen`, `bg-screenWhite`, `font-body`, etc.).

Do not duplicate `<html>`/`<body>` in nested layouts.

## 5) Provider and shell composition (reference)

Inside `<body>`, order matters for UX and context:

1. **Site-wide providers** that wrap both shell and pages—e.g. `ModalProvider` wrapping everything that can open modals.
2. **Global shell** that should appear on (almost) every route—e.g. `NavBarShell` inside **`Suspense`** with a lightweight fallback (spinner) so async work in the nav does not block the rest of the document from streaming where applicable.
3. **`{children}`** — the active route segment’s page tree; keep it as a direct sibling to other persistent shell regions when they share the same provider.
4. **Global portal UI** — e.g. a single `<Modal />` **after** `{children}` but still inside `ModalProvider`, matching the reference.

**Rules:**

- One `ModalProvider` + one `<Modal />` at the root unless the product intentionally uses a different modal system in a subtree (not the Soul Academy default).
- Prefer **`Suspense`** around components that suspend or that you want to isolate with a dedicated fallback; avoid wrapping `{children}` in Suspense at the root unless you have a deliberate full-page loading UX.

## 6) Nested layouts (when you add them)

- Nested `layout.tsx` files wrap **only** their segment: import segment providers, render segment chrome, then `{children}`.
- Do not re-import `globals.css` or re-apply all font variables unless a subtree truly needs a divergent shell (normally **never** at nested levels—inherit from root).

## 7) What not to put in layouts

- Data fetching for a single page’s content (belongs in `page.tsx` or a server component colocated with that route).
- Auth-only redirects for one route (prefer middleware or page-level checks unless the entire subtree is gated the same way).
- Heavy client trees—push to `_components` and import lean wrappers into the layout.

## 8) Checklist for new or edited layouts

- [ ] Default export wraps `{children}` (and any slots) correctly.
- [ ] Root: single `html`/`body`, fonts + global body classes, `globals.css` imported once here.
- [ ] Providers wrap every consumer that needs them; portal siblings (`Modal`) remain inside the same provider as openers.
- [ ] `metadata` / `viewport` updated when product name or scaling policy changes.
- [ ] No page-specific business UI creeping into the root shell.
